    <body.head>
      <hedline>
        <hl1>The City That Never Sweeps</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <byline class="print_byline">By Ray Corio</byline>
      <byline class="normalized_byline">Corio, Ray</byline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Possibility of New York Yankees sweeping New York Mets in World Series discussed (S)</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>Mets fans can keep their chins up and Yankees fans can keep their brooms in the closet: there has never been a four-game sweep in a Subway Series.</p>
        <p>The closest thing in the first 13 such series came in 1922. The New York Giants won the opener from the Yankees, but Game 2 was suspended by darkness after 10 innings in a 3-3 tie. The Giants won the next three games to complete a 4-0-1 sweep in five games.</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>Mets fans can keep their chins up and Yankees fans can keep their brooms in the closet: there has never been a four-game sweep in a Subway Series.</p>
        <p>The closest thing in the first 13 such series came in 1922. The New York Giants won the opener from the Yankees, but Game 2 was suspended by darkness after 10 innings in a 3-3 tie. The Giants won the next three games to complete a 4-0-1 sweep in five games.</p>
        <p>Fifteen years later, the 1937 Yankees were 4-1 winners over the Giants in the Subway Series. In both 1941 and 1949, the Yankees beat the Brooklyn Dodgers, four games to one.</p>
        <p>Ray Corio</p>
        <p>BASEBALL: SUBWAY SERIES -- NOTEBOOK</p>
      </block>
